title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 50, 12 gauge auto-loading shotgun
postcontent:
Winchester Model 50, 12 gauge auto-loading shotgun.
Winchester only produced 196,400 Model 50s between 1954 and 1961. Winchester stopped production because it was too expensive to manufacture, and the profit margin per unit was too low. A true “pre-64 Winchester”, the Model 50 is considered a well built and reliable shotgun – it has all machined parts and no stamped, cast or plastic anywhere. It is a short bolt blowback action with a floating chamber, and the first production autoloader with a non-recoiling barrel (the Browning A5 and the Remington 48 have recoiling barrels). This shotgun is at 98% (almost pristine bluing and stock) swings and tracks quickly, making it a favorite with many champion skeet and trap shooters.
This particular shotgun was manufactured in 1961 and features a 28 inch full fixed choke barrel and walnut “field grade” stocks with factory hand-cut checkering. The stock is free of cracks, chips, deep scratches, or gouges but may have some light handling marks. There is no rust, pitting, or cracks in the metal. This is a NICE gun!Serious Inquiries Only!
Add this rare Winchester to your collection, or take it into the field next season!
Must be willing to sign a Bill of Sale and have a valid CCP.

title: For Sale/Trade:  WW2 Japanese Katana
postcontent: I bought this 10 years ago from an estate auction (guy had a bunch of cool military stuff). I've done some more research and have been contacted by some knowledgeable individuals sharing their information and here is was I've learned; this isnt an authentic WW2 military sword but it's not a Chinese knockoff either. This blade is a Japanese handmade folded steel blade (not made with Tamahagane steel though) made in Japan in the 60's and 70's to look like a WW2 Katana. The Hamon isn't present because someone probably polished the blade, it might come back with an acid etch though. But the blade is still a very beautiful pattern welded (Damascus) with minimal spotted surface rust. Also I've  been told that the scabbard or Saya could be an original WW2 but that's unknown for sure. It's a shame it isn't an authentic WW2 katana but it's a Japanese made katana and a pretty cool conversation piece as well.$250 OBO open to trades
